<p>I know i can make <code>ffmpeg</code> put its output to <code>stdout</code> and <code>stderr</code> using <code>pipe:1</code> and <code>pipe:2</code>, respectively, as <code>output_file</code> parameter. (<a href="http://ffmpeg.org/ffmpeg-protocols.html#pipe" rel="nofollow">Docs</a>)</p>  <p>But what about <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Named_pipe" rel="nofollow">named pipes</a>, can i make it write to one?</p>  <p>If not, is there a way to redirect the data in <code>stdout</code> to a named pipe in Linux? (something like <code>ffmpeg &lt;parameters&gt; | pipe123</code>)</p>  <p>This question is a follow-up of <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/32563527/how-to-keep-piping-output-of-a-program-to-a-python-script-if-the-program-is-res">this question</a>.</p>